    value: 凡
english:
  title: Imperial Rescript Denying Song An-guk's Request to Decline the Position of Left Minister of the Chancellery
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    ...In the Han dynasty, the Left and Right Ministers served to assist the Minister of the Chancellery and the Vice-Minister in governing the affairs of the Secretariat. Through succeeding ages into Wei and Jin times, only the Left Minister retained the authority to impeach the Eight Seats of government, earning the title "Censor of the Court." How difficult it is indeed to find one worthy of such a post!

    You possess gravity of bearing and spare words sufficient to calm the restless hearts of men. Your resolute wisdom and clear judgment are equal to managing great affairs. Having ventured forth into military service and long assisted in strategic counsel, your service merits recognition through special advancement. Thus do I confer upon you the position of Left Minister of the Chancellery, entrusting you with authority over the Central Administration.

    Know that rank and stipend exist to reward service. Your deeds in battle would merit advancement beyond the ordinary rank, which none could fault. Moreover, you have served in the fourth rank for many years already—by seniority alone you are due promotion. This appointment is therefore merely regular advancement according to your tenure, not extraordinary elevation by reason of merit. Why then do you hesitate and demur? ...
  footnotes:
    - The 'Eight Seats' (八座) refers to the eight highest ministerial positions in the imperial government, whose holders could be impeached only by the Left Minister of the Chancellery.
    - This is an imperial rescript responding to an official's polite refusal of promotion, a common literary form in East Asian bureaucratic tradition.
